data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Inventory

| API | Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|----------|---------|-------------|
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop` | Blocking call interruption | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop` | Cancellable work loop fallback | Remove — cooperative cancellation handles this |

## Key Pitfalls in This Code

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** on .NET 8 — it simply doesn't work.
2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046`)** — it only wakes threads in `WaitSleepJoin` state and throws a *different* exception (`ThreadInterruptedException`), making control flow fragile.
3. **Race condition in the original**: multiple `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` lose signals — only one item gets dequeued per wake. The migrated version fixes this with a drain loop.
4. **`ManualResetEvent` won't respond to cancellation** — you must use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` so the blocked thread wakes on cancel.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Blocks until signaled OR cancelled — replaces Thread.Interrupt wake-up
            try
            {
                _newEvent.Wait(token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                break; // Stop was called — exit cleanly
            }

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original race condition)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        // Cooperative cancellation — replaces Thread.Interrupt + Thread.Abort
        _cts.Cancel();
        _thread?.Join(5000);
        // No Thread.Abort fallback needed — the loop checks the token and exits
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` | `ManualResetEventSlim` | Lighter weight; `.Wait(CancellationToken)` built in |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative cancellation checkpoint |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `_newEvent.Wait(token)` | Wakes on cancel *and* signal — no `Interrupt` needed |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Token cancellation wakes the blocked `.Wait()` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Removed entirely | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` added | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEventSlim` must be disposed |
| Dequeue one item per wake | Drain loop | Fixes lost-signal race when multiple items enqueued between wake cycles |

> **If `Handle()` is long-running**, pass `_cts.Token` into it and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside — otherwise cancellation stalls until the current item finishes.
